This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it explores the geometrical and topological properties of decision regions produced by deep neural networks. It also involves the use of differential geometry and topology to analyze the decision boundaries, which suggests a focus on mathematical and theoretical aspects of machine learning. Additionally, the paper may also fall under computer vision (cs.CV) as it deals with classification performance and robustness against adversarial attacks. Neural networks (cs.NE), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and information theory (cs.IT) are also possible sub-categories as they are related to the study of deep neural networks and their properties.
